            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Inverse square law for sound – formulas</h2>
              <p>
                The inverse square law describes how sound intensity decreases
                as you move away from a point source in a free field. As
                distance doubles, intensity drops to one quarter and sound
                pressure level (SPL) drops by about 6 dB.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Intensity vs distance</p>
                <p class="mb-2">
                  For a point source emitting power \(P\) uniformly in all
                  directions:
                </p>
                <p>\[ I(r) = \frac{P}{4\pi r^2} \]</p>
                <p class="mt-2">For two distances \(r_1\) and \(r_2\):</p>
                <p>\[ \frac{I_2}{I_1} = \left(\frac{r_1}{r_2}\right)^2 \]</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Sound pressure level (SPL) vs distance
                </p>
                <p>
                  Because SPL in decibels is proportional to the logarithm of
                  pressure (or intensity), the level at distance \(r_2\) is:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ L_2 = L_1 - 20 \log_{10}\left(\frac{r_2}{r_1}\right) \]
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  The level difference between two distances is:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \Delta L = L_2 - L_1 = 20
                  \log_{10}\left(\frac{r_1}{r_2}\right) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Typical distance vs level changes</h3>
              <p>
                The table below assumes an ideal point source in a free field
                (no reflections, no air absorption).
              </p>

              <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
