                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">4×</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use this inverse square law sound calculator</h2>

              <h3>1. SPL vs distance mode</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the reference level L₁</strong> – for example,
                  94 dB SPL at 1 m from a loudspeaker.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the reference distance r₁</strong> – usually 1 m
                  or 1 ft.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the new distance r₂</strong> – where you want to
                  know the level.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Calculate SPL at r₂”</strong> to see:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Level drop ΔL in dB.</li>
                    <li>New level L₂ at r₂.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>2. Intensity vs distance mode</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>intensity I₁</strong> (in W/m² or relative
                  units) at distance r₁.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter <strong>r₁</strong> and <strong>r₂</strong> using the
                  same units.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Calculate Intensity at r₂”</strong> to get I₂
                  and the intensity ratio I₂ / I₁.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>3. Compare two distances</h3>
              <p>
                If you only care about how much louder or quieter the sound is
                between two distances, use the
                <strong>Compare Two Distances</strong> mode:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Enter <strong>r₁</strong> and <strong>r₂</strong>.</li>
                <li>Click <strong>“Compare r₁ and r₂”</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  The tool shows:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Level difference ΔL in dB.</li>
                    <li>Intensity ratio I₂ / I₁.</li>
                    <li>Distance ratio r₂ / r₁.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Question:</strong> A loudspeaker produces 94 dB SPL at 1
                m. What is the level at 8 m?
              </p>
              <p>
                Here, \(L_1 = 94\ \text{dB}\), \(r_1 = 1\ \text{m}\), \(r_2 = 8\
                \text{m}\).
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ L_2 = L_1 - 20 \log_{10}\left(\frac{r_2}{r_1}\right) = 94 -
                  20 \log_{10}(8) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \log_{10}(8) \approx 0.9031 \Rightarrow 20 \log_{10}(8)
                  \approx 18.06\ \text{dB} \]
                </p>
                <p>\[ L_2 \approx 94 - 18.06 = 75.9\ \text{dB} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                So at 8 m, the level is about <strong>76 dB SPL</strong>,
                roughly 18 dB quieter than at 1 m.
              </p>

              <h2>Assumptions and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Point source:</strong> The law assumes the source is
                  small compared with the distance (far-field).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Free field:</strong> No reflections from walls, floor,
                  or ceiling; sound spreads spherically.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>No air absorption:</strong> At long distances and high
                  frequencies, air absorption can add extra loss.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>No directionality:</strong> Real loudspeakers are
                  directional; off-axis levels can be lower.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Background noise:</strong> The law predicts sound from
                  the source only, not ambient noise.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is the inverse square law for sound?</h3>
              <p>
                It states that sound intensity is inversely proportional to the
                square of the distance from a point source: \(I \propto 1/r^2\).
                In practice, this means that every time you double the distance,
                intensity drops to one quarter and SPL drops by 6 dB.
              </p>

              <h3>How many dB do you lose when you double the distance?</h3>
              <p>
                For an ideal point source in a free field, doubling the distance
                causes a <strong>6 dB</strong> drop in sound pressure level.
                Halving the distance gives a 6 dB increase.
              </p>

              <h3>Does the inverse square law work indoors?</h3>
              <p>
                Only approximately. In small or reverberant rooms, reflections
                from surfaces add energy, so level falls off more slowly than 6
                dB per distance doubling once you are beyond the direct-field
                region.
              </p>

              <h3>What about line arrays or long sources?</h3>
              <p>
                Long line sources (e.g., tall column speakers or line arrays)
                can behave closer to a <strong>cylindrical</strong> wavefront
                over some range, giving about <strong>3 dB</strong> loss per
                distance doubling instead of 6 dB. The calculator here assumes a
                point (spherical) source.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for underwater acoustics?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, the geometric spreading part (inverse square) still applies
                for a point source in a homogeneous medium. Just choose the
                appropriate dB reference (e.g., dB re 1 µPa). However,
                underwater propagation often includes additional effects
                (boundary reflections, absorption, refraction) that this simple
                model does not cover.
              </p>
